Pacific Public Health Surveillance Network <PACNET@IDEFIX.SPC.ORG.NC>

The following background data on dengue in New Caledonia were extracted
from the GIDEON software program:
- Dengue was first reported in New Caledonia in 1910, and outbreaks were
reported in 1908, 1926, and 1943 to 1944. An epidemic during 1971 to 1972
involved at least 40% of the population.
- 66 cases of dengue hemorrhagic fever (DHF) were reported during 1975 to
1979; 160 during 1980 to 1984; 662 during 1985 to 1989; 119 during 1990 to
1993.
- No cases of dengue were reported in 1978. In 1979, an outbreak involved
11% of persons on Thio (Noumea), with 5 cases of DHF (only 118 cases were
officially reported from New Caledonia that year). An estimated 25,000
were infected during an outbreak in 1989.
- 1,820 cases (563 of these in Noumea) including 37 DHF were confirmed
during January to June 1995 - 60% from Southern Province and 40% from
Northern Province. 243 cases were reported in 1997
--
Steve Berger
Tel Aviv Medical Center
